1. Data Cleaning

Reading the data into R

ic <- readxl::read_xlsx(paste0(path_ic_data,"/De-identified covariates data.xlsx"))

Renaming columns: The column names were changed to make it suitable for analysis

colnames(ic) <- c("id","cases",
                  "age_last_visit","gender","race","smoking",
                  "elmiron","hydroxyzine","tca","gabapentin","hydroxychloroquine",
                  "cyclobenzaprine","methenamine","phenazopyridine","oxybutynin")
ic <- ic[!is.na(ic$id),]

Labeling different columns

ic$cases <- as.factor(ic$cases)
levels(ic$cases) <- c("1 Definite","2 Possibly", "3 Not", "4 No images")
table(ic$cases,useNA = "always")
## 
##  1 Definite  2 Possibly       3 Not 4 No images        <NA>

ic$gender <- as.factor(ic$gender)
levels(ic$gender) <- c("1 Male", "2 Female")
table(ic$gender, useNA= "always")

ic$elmiron <- with(ic,ifelse(!is.na(elmiron),1,0))
ic$hydroxyzine <- with(ic,ifelse(!is.na(hydroxyzine),1,0))
ic$tca <- with(ic,ifelse(!is.na(tca),1,0))

ic$hydroxychloroquine <- with(ic,ifelse(!is.na(hydroxychloroquine),1,0))

ic$phenazopyridine <- with(ic,ifelse(!is.na(phenazopyridine),1,0))
ic$oxybutynin <- with(ic,ifelse(!is.na(oxybutynin),1,0))

ic <- ic %>% mutate_at(c("elmiron","hydroxyzine",
                         "tca","gabapentin","hydroxychloroquine",
                         "cyclobenzaprine","methenamine",
                         "phenazopyridine","oxybutynin"),
                       funs(factor(.,labels=c("no","yes"))))

ggplot(data=ic,aes(x=age_last_visit,group=outcome,fill=outcome)) + geom_histogram(alpha=0.2) + theme_bw()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

There is slight deviation from normality for Age in Last Visit for those who had Outcome = Yes. This is likely due to sample size issues.

ggplot(data=ic,aes(sample=age_last_visit)) + geom_qq() + geom_qq_line() + facet_grid(~outcome) + theme_bw()

Levenes test for Equality of variance does not reject the null hypothesis (Variances are equal)

car::leveneTest(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value  Pr(>F)  
## group   1   3.414 0.06602 .
##       214                  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

We will use Independent Two-sample T-test (Pooled) We do not reject the null hypothesis that age at last visit is different across the outcome groups

t.test(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic,var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age_last_visit by outcome
## t = -0.23212, df = 214, p-value = 0.8167
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -7.042806  5.558827
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group no mean in group yes 
##          61.17801          61.92000

Wilcoxon Rank Sum test confirms the above result.

wilcox.test(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic,var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  age_last_visit by outcome
## W = 2385, p-value = 0.9946
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
We will use the results from Fishers exact tests

-Yates correction for Chi-squared was applied for all comparisons.

a. confounding by Hydroxyzine

Hydroxyzine is a confounder in the relationship of Elmiron to Outcome. It is associated with Elmiron.

fisher.test(ic$elmiron,ic$hydroxyzine)
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  ic$elmiron and ic$hydroxyzine
## p-value = 0.0337
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.046401 4.126925
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##     2.0683

On adjusting for hydroxyzine in the model, it only modifies the relationship slightly. We can choose to not include hydroxyzine in the model since it doesnt modify the OR (2.26 to 2.21 with p<0.001).

With Hydroxyzine: AIC = 142.79 Without Hydroxyzine: AIC = 141.52

There is slight deviation from normality for Age in Last Visit for those who had Outcome = Yes. This is likely due to sample size issues.

ggplot(data=ic,aes(sample=age_last_visit)) + geom_qq() + geom_qq_line() + facet_grid(~outcome)

Levenes test for Equality of variance does not reject the null hypothesis (Variances are equal)

car::leveneTest(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value  Pr(>F)  
## group   1  3.0693 0.08122 .
##       214                  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

We will use Independent Two-sample T-test (Pooled) We do not reject the null hypothesis that age at last visit is different across the outcome groups

t.test(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic,var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age_last_visit by outcome
## t = 1.008, df = 214, p-value = 0.3146
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -3.991508 12.346529
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group no mean in group yes 
##          61.53465          57.35714

Wilcoxon Rank Sum test confirms the above result.

wilcox.test(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic,var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  age_last_visit by outcome
## W = 1704.5, p-value = 0.1995
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

There is slight deviation from normality for Age in Last Visit for those who had Outcome = Yes. This is likely due to sample size issues.

Levenes test for Equality of variance does not reject the null hypothesis (Variances are equal)

car::leveneTest(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value Pr(>F)  
## group   1  3.2755 0.0718 .
##       203                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

We will use Independent Two-sample T-test (Pooled) We do not reject the null hypothesis that age at last visit is different across the outcome groups

t.test(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic,var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  age_last_visit by outcome
## t = 0.91288, df = 203, p-value = 0.3624
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -4.431757 12.073492
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group no mean in group yes 
##          61.17801          57.35714

Wilcoxon Rank Sum test confirms the above result.

wilcox.test(age_last_visit~outcome,data=ic,var.equal=TRUE)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  age_last_visit by outcome
## W = 1588, p-value = 0.2421
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

C. Multiple Logistic

Adjusting for age, gender, race and smoking status The AIC for this model is higher than for the parsimonious model. Explanation: This model with more variables is penalized for its fit which is probably similar to the model with Elmiron alone.

summary(glm(relevel(ic$outcome, ref = "no") ~ race + age_last_visit + gender + smoking + elmiron,
            data=ic,family="binomial"))
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
